excerpt: Kalpetta is a town in the mountainous Wayanad region of Kerala, South India. Itâ€™s a gateway to the trails of lofty Chembra Peak and to Neelimala Viewpoint, which overlooks waterfalls and forested valleys. North of town, the traditional, Dravidian-style Ananthanatha Swami Jain Temple is perched on a hilltop surrounded by coffee plantations. To the southeast, Meppadi is a scenic village with lush tea estates.
detail_description: Kalpetta, a charming town nestled in the mountainous Wayanad region of Kerala, South India, serves as a perfect base for exploring the breathtaking trails of Chembra Peak and Neelimala Viewpoint. The area is adorned with cascading waterfalls and lush valleys, offering stunning vistas. Visitors can also visit the Ananthanatha Swami Jain Temple with its traditional Dravidian-style architecture set amidst picturesque coffee plantations.
name: Kalpetta

excerpt: Scenic, freshwater lake offering pedal-boating & a perimeter trail with a lush backdrop of trees.
detail_description: Pookode Lake is a picturesque freshwater lake in Wayanad, surrounded by lush greenery and offering activities like pedal-boating. It's one of the many attractions in the area, which also include Banasura Sagar Dam, Kuruva Island, Tholpetty Wildlife Sanctuary, Edakkal Caves, Meenmutty Waterfalls, and more.
name: Pookode Lake

detail_description: Ananthanatha Swamy Jain Temple, also known as Puliyarmala Jain Temple, is a significant pilgrimage site in Kalpetta. It is one of the oldest temples in Kerala, dating back to the 13th century and showcasing remarkable Jain architecture. The temple is dedicated to Ananthanatha Swami, a revered Tirthankar in Jainism. Along with the Koottamundu Glass Temple, it highlights the historical presence of Jains in this region.
name: Ananthanatha Swamy Jain Temple
address: J3RP+9P9, Kalpetta - Mananthavadi Road, Puliyarmala, Kainatty Junction, Kalpetta, Kerala 673122, India

detail_description: Koottamundu is a significant pilgrimage site for Jains, featuring the impressive Glass Temple dedicated to the revered Jain saint Parshawanatha Swami. Nestled on the hillside of Vellarimala, about 22 km from Kalpetta, this sacred place attracts devotees who seek to pay homage and engage in meditation.
name: Koottamundu

excerpt: Wayanad is a rural district in Kerala state, southwest India. In the east, the Wayanad Wildlife Sanctuary is a lush, forested region with areas of high altitude, home to animals including Asiatic elephants, tigers, leopards and egrets. In the Ambukuthi Hills to the south, Edakkal Caves contain ancient petroglyphs, some dating back to the Neolithic age.
detail_description: Wayanad, a rural district in Kerala, India, is known for its lush Wayanad Wildlife Sanctuary where Asiatic elephants, tigers, and leopards roam. The region's high-altitude forests are also home to egrets. In the south, the Ambukuthi Hills house the ancient Edakkal Caves with Neolithic petroglyphs.
name: Wayanad

detail_description: The Wayanad Tea Museum, located 13 km from the city center of Wayanad, Kerala, offers a captivating journey into the history and production of tea in the region. Surrounded by lush tea plantations, this museum provides an immersive experience that educates visitors about various stages of tea production. From learning about the history and types of tea in India to witnessing antique machines used in earlier times, visitors can also enjoy a cafe on the top floor offering delightful teas like mint lemon tea.
name: Wayanad Tea Museum
address: J227+6VR, Achoor Estate Road, Achooranam, Pozhuthana, Achoor, Kerala 673575, India

excerpt: Vythiri is a town located in Wayanad district in the Indian state of Kerala. Along with Mananthavady and Sulthan Bathery, it is one of the three taluks in the district. 2.084 sq. km is the total area of vythiri. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Vythiri, situated in the picturesque Wayanad district of Kerala, is a charming tourist destination. This small village offers a tranquil escape for travelers seeking natural beauty and cultural experiences. As one of the three Taluks in the district, Vythiri provides a serene setting for visitors to immerse themselves in the local way of life and explore the stunning surroundings.
name: Vythiri

excerpt: Meppadi is a small town in the Indian state of Kerala. It is a scenic hill station on the State Highway between Kozhikode and Ooty. The nearest city is Kalpetta, which is the headquarters of the Wayanad revenue district. Wikipedia.
name: Meppadi
Mayiladippara Chandranatha Giri - Shri Chandranatha Swamy Digambar Jain Temple

detail_description: Lourde Matha Church Pallikunnu, also known as Lady of Lourdes, Pallikkunnu Church, is a significant tourist attraction in Wayanad, Kerala. Established in 1908 by a French priest named Fr. Jefreno, it is one of the oldest churches in the area and holds great historical importance.
name: OUR LADY OF LOURDES SHRINE, PALLIKUNNU
address: Pallikunnu Via Kalpetta, Chundakara, Wayanad, Kerala 673124, India

detail_description: Kurumbalakotta is a monolithic hillock located in Wayanad district, Kerala, India. It stands at an elevation of 3,220 feet above sea level and is situated just 5 km from the city center. This destination offers breathtaking panoramic views of the surrounding landscape and serves as a convergence point between the Eastern and Western Ghats. Although there is no defined path, it attracts adventurous trekkers seeking an extra thrill during their journey.
name: Kurumbalakotta

detail_description: Chain Tree Architects&Developers is a renowned architectural firm in Wayanad, known for its unique and creative designs that blend modern and traditional elements seamlessly. The firm's young and dynamic team is praised for their innovative thinking and great skills, offering a one-stop solution for all engineering needs. Their stunning designs are highly recommended, reflecting a perfect combination of nature and contemporary elements.
name: Chain Tree Architects&Developers
address: H3WP+V3H, Meppadi Rd, Madiyur, Kalpetta, Kerala 673122, India

name: Varadoor Shri Ananthanatha Swami Digambar Jain Temple

detail_description: The Poopoli Wayanad Flower Show is just one of the many attractions in Wayanad.
name: WAYANAD FLOWER SHOW

detail_description: Day Dreams Home Stay Wayanad offers a unique experience of staying in a treehouse, making it one of the best things to do in Kerala. The wooden houses are nestled amidst nature and offer various packages that include activities like bonfires, rock climbing, rappelling, and nature walks. It's an ideal place for those seeking an adventurous yet tranquil getaway in Wayanad.
name: Day Dreams Home Stay Wayanad

excerpt: Reached by hiking, these remote caves feature petroglyphs from the Stone Age, plus scenic views.
detail_description: Edakkal Caves, located in a remote area 25 kilometers away from Wayanad, are two natural caves formed due to the sons of Lord Rama. These caves are famous for their archaeological significance and unique rock formations with ancient engravings dating back to the Neolithic era. The prehistoric caves feature exquisite rock carvings and walls, situated at an elevation of 1,200 meters above sea level.
name: Edakkal Caves

excerpt: Monkeys frequent this compact lookout point along a highway with mountain & valley views.
detail_description: Lakkidi View Point is located at an elevation of 2296 feet on the border of Kozhikode and Wayanad. It provides a stunning panoramic view of the valley below, offering a bird's-eye perspective of the plains and highway.
name: Lakkidi View Point
address: G269+VHF, Kozhikode-Mysore-Kollegal Highway, Lakkidi, Kerala 673576, India

excerpt: 3-tiered waterfall with a pool at the base for swimming, reachable by a 10 to 15 minute forest hike.
detail_description: Soochipara Waterfalls is a stunning 3-tiered waterfall in Wayanad, offering a refreshing pool at the base where visitors can take a dip after a scenic 10 to 15-minute hike through the forest. This natural wonder is just one of the many attractions in Wayanad, which also include Banasura Dam, Chembra Peak, Edakkal Caves, Kuruva Dweep, and more.
name: Soochipara Waterfalls

detail_description: Wayanad Wildlife Sanctuary, Tholpetty, is a part of the Banasurasagar Project and offers a picturesque sight with the Banasura hills in the background. The sanctuary features various forest types including tropical moist dry deciduous and semi-evergreen forests, along with teak, eucalyptus, silver oak, and rosewood plantations covering about one third of the area.
name: Tholpetty Range - Wayanad Wildlife Sanctuary

excerpt: A 3-hour hike leads to the top of this lush mountain with a waterfall & an earth dam at its base.
detail_description: Banasura Hill, located in Wayanad, Kerala, is renowned for its 3-hour hike that leads to the top of this lush mountain. At the base of the hill lies an earth dam and a stunning waterfall. The trek offers breathtaking views and encounters with diverse wildlife such as wild boars, elephants, and deer.
name: Banasura Hill

excerpt: Natural setting with a 3-tiered waterfall accessible by challenging hike on muddy terrain.
detail_description: Makkiyad Meenmutty Water Falls is a stunning three-tiered waterfall located 29 kilometers from Kalpetta town in Wayanad District. The waterfall offers a spectacular 300-foot drop and is surrounded by breathtaking natural scenery, making it an ideal destination for tourists and business travelers seeking a peaceful retreat. Accessible via a challenging hike through muddy terrain, the falls are well-maintained with clear directions along the way.
name: Makkiyad Meenmutty Water Falls
address: Korome- Karimbil Rd, Thondernad, Kanjirangad, Kerala 670731, India

excerpt: Small waterfall with a shallow pool popular for swimming, family picnics & natural scenery.
detail_description: Kanthanpara Waterfalls is a charming little waterfall located near Meppadi in the Wayanad district of Kerala. It's a popular spot for swimming, family picnics, and enjoying the natural scenery. Surrounded by lush green tea estates, the waterfall offers picturesque walking trails that are perfect for nature walks and camping. The area upstream is also known for its scenic beauty, making it an ideal location for nature lovers to enjoy with friends and family amidst coffee plantations.
name: Kanthanpara Waterfalls

detail_description: The Ancient Jain Temple, also known as the Sulthan Bathery Jain Temple, is a significant historical site located in a serene and picturesque town. The temple dates back to the 13th century and showcases the dominant architectural style of the Vijayanagara dynasty. Surrounded by lush green hills and vast grasslands, it offers visitors a tranquil ambiance for contemplation. The intricate carvings and spiritual significance make it an ideal destination for those interested in India's rich heritage.
name: Jain Temple, Sulthan Bathery
address: M762+377, Bangalore-Calicut Highway, Sultan Bathery, Kerala 673592, India

detail_description: Neelimala View Point in Wayanad offers a stunning panoramic view of the Meenmutty Waterfalls, mountain ranges, and wildlife of The Nilgiris. The best time to visit is after a summer rain when the cloud bed creates an excellent view. However, visitors should be cautious as there are wildlife presence in the morning, including bison and big cats during early mornings and late evenings. It's a great spot for nature enthusiasts seeking breathtaking views of the surrounding landscape.
name: Neelimala View Point

excerpt: Iconic national park known for its vast bird population & hiking trails through evergreen forest.
detail_description: Pakshipathalam, located in Wayanad, is a renowned national park celebrated for its diverse bird population and extensive hiking trails that wind through lush evergreen forests. In addition to this iconic sanctuary, visitors can explore various other attractions such as Banasura Sagar Dam, Kuruva Island, Tholpetty Wildlife Sanctuary, Edakkal Caves, Meenmutty Waterfalls, and many more. Each site boasts its own rich heritage and history.
name: Pakshipathalam
